In [3]:
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df.Longitude, df.Latitude))
gdf = gdf.set_crs("EPSG:4326")
gdf = gdf.to_crs("EPSG:26916")

The regimes model requires that you have a certain number of points in each regime. For our regimes, we are using the Town Code which is provided by the dataset.

This is a common set of quantitiative variables shared across all of these models. We take a random sample of size 2.5% and ensure that it is the same 8,107 data points by seeding the random number generator with random_state=0.

In [5]:
i_vars = [
    'Age',
    'Bedrooms',  
    'Building Square Feet', 
    'Estimate (Building)', 
    'Estimate (Land)', 
    'Fireplaces', 
    'Full Baths',
    'Garage 1 Area',
    'Garage 2 Area', 
    'Half Baths', 
    'Land Square Feet',
    'Rooms',
    'Sale Quarter'

gdf = gdf[my_rows]
gdf = gdf.sample(frac=.025, random_state=0)
print("Dataframe has {} rows and {} columns".format(len(gdf), len(list(gdf.columns))))
X = gdf[i_vars].values
y = gdf[dep_var].values.ravel()

Create the spatial weight matrix using k-nearest neighbors with K=64.

In [6]:
# determine weight matrix
w = KNN.from_dataframe(gdf, k=64) # needed k large enough that it was connected
#w = DistanceBand.from_dataframe(gdf,threshold=.0075) # needed k large enough that it was connected

Transform the weight matrix to normalize by rows.

In [7]:
w.transform = 'R'

In the code below we are calculating the Spatial Lag Model with Regimes, allowing the intercept to vary across regimes, but not other variables (this is controlled by cols2regi argument).

In [8]:
rslm = spreg.ML_Lag_Regimes(y, X, w=w,
                            regimes=list(gdf["Town Code"]),
                            name_x=i_vars, name_y="Sale Price",
                            cols2regi=[False]*len(i_vars))

Looking at the model fit:

  • The $R^{2}$ of 0.77 is the lowest of all of the models meaning that 77% of the variation in Sales Price can be explained by the model. This is the highest of all of the models!
  • The AIC of 11,299 is the second lowest among all of the models, which is quite impressive paried with the high $R^2$

We will look at the residuals first and then dive into the varied intercepts.

The residuals above are quite good: generally bouncing around 0 with no clear trend. The Moran's I of 0.01 is very good, second only to SEM. In the cell below we are copying the model's intercept for each town to the geodataframe.

In [14]:
# trying to get it so we can plot based on town code beta
town_codes = sorted(list(set(gdf["Town Code"])))
gdf_town_codes = list(gdf["Town Code"])
regime_betas = [ rslm.betas[town_codes.index(code), 0] for code in gdf_town_codes ]
gdf["SLMRegimeBeta"] = regime_betas

In the cell below you can see the intercept as it varies across our regimes (Town Codes). The bright yellow dot in the middle of the county is Oak Park which indicates that the location is highly desirable even when controlling for attributes of the house like the number of bedrooms, etc. However, it is important to determine which of these intercepts are statistically significant which we will do in the next map.

In [15]:
cmap=matplotlib.cm.viridis
norm=matplotlib.colors.Normalize(vmin=min(gdf["SLMRegimeBeta"]), vmax=max(gdf["SLMRegimeBeta"]))
ax = gdf.plot(column="SLMRegimeBeta", legend=True, figsize=(12,8), alpha=0.5, cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
plt.title("Intercept by Town Code")
plt.show()
In [16]:
# trying to get it so we can plot based on town code beta
town_codes = sorted(list(set(gdf["Town Code"])))
gdf_town_codes = list(gdf["Town Code"])
regime_betas = [ float(rslm.betas[town_codes.index(code), 0]) if rslm.z_stat[town_codes.index(code)][1] < 0.05 else float('inf') for code in gdf_town_codes ]
gdf["SLMRegimeBetaIfSig"] = regime_betas

In the map below we mask out statistically insignificant intercepts by plotting them as gray. It seems about half of the intercepts are statistically significant. Just as with SEM+Regimes, Oak Park has a statistically significant and highly postive intercept. It is difficult to tell the pattern with the rest of the towns having significant intercepts.
